# Presentation Widget Rules

## Description
Rules for files inside `presentation/widgets/`. Widgets are reusable visual building blocks that receive data and callbacks from screens instead of owning feature orchestration.

## Responsibilities
- Keep exactly one widget class per file.
- Use clear widget names that describe purpose.
- Pass all changeable UI values through constructor arguments or project tokens.
- Keep input state outside widgets. Widgets receive current value and validation and report changes via callbacks.
- Do not access feature BLoCs directly. Pass data in and expose callbacks out.
- Do not own navigation. Screens handle router calls and widgets expose intent callbacks such as `onTap`, `onRetry`, or `onDelete`.
- Prefer `AppSpacing` and `AppRadii` over raw design values when they fit.
- Avoid magic numbers when a token, named constant, or parameter would be clearer.
- Prefer inline composition over widget-returning helper methods.
- Use layout constraints that fit scroll direction and parent size.
- Prefer `const` constructors and widgets whenever possible.
- Follow `presentation-layer.mdc` for shared localization, context extension, null-safety, and form-state rules.

## Green Flags
- A widget file contains one clearly named widget class.
- The widget receives text, state, and actions through constructor parameters.
- A text field widget exposes `onChanged` and receives current value and error text from above.
- Reusable widgets stay visual and stateless from the feature orchestration perspective.

## Red Flags
- Two widget classes in one file.
- Calling `context.read`, `context.watch`, `context.select`, `BlocBuilder`, `BlocListener`, or router APIs inside reusable feature widgets.
- Owning navigation or feature decisions inside a widget instead of exposing callbacks.
- Using widget-returning helper methods instead of inline composition or a dedicated widget file.
